# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: afl-women-s
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:afl-women-s/1897-vfl-season] The **1897 VFL season** was the inaugural season of the Victorian Football League (VFL), the highest-level senior Australian rules football competition in Victoria.
[src:afl-women-s/1897-vfl-season] The season ran from 8 May to 4 September, comprising a 14-round home-and-away season followed by a three-week finals series featuring the top four clubs.
[src:afl-women-s/1897-vfl-season] Eight Victorian Football Association (VFA) clubs – Carlton, Collingwood, Essendon, Fitzroy, Geelong, Melbourne, South Melbourne and St Kilda – featured in the inaugural season after seceding from the VFA in 1896.
[src:afl-women-s/1897-vfl-season] Essendon won the inaugural premiership after winning all three of its finals matches, with Geelong finishing as runners-up with two wins.
[src:afl-women-s/1897-vfl-season] Geelong won the minor premiership by finishing atop the home-and-away ladder with an 11–3 win–loss record.
[src:afl-women-s/1897-vfl-season] Geelong's Eddy James and Melbourne's Jack Leith tied for the leading goalkicker medal as the league's leading goalkickers.
[src:afl-women-s/1897-vfl-season] In 1897, the VFL competition consisted of eight teams of 20 on-the-field players each, with no "reserves" (although any of the 20 players who had left the playing field for any reason could later resume their place on the field at any time during the match).
[src:afl-women-s/1897-vfl-season] Each team played each other twice in a home-and-away season of 14 rounds.
[src:afl-women-s/1897-vfl-season] Once the 14-round home-and-away season had finished, the 1897 VFL Premiers were determined according to the conditions dictated by the specific format and conventions of the 1897 Finals System, which was used in this season only.
[src:afl-women-s/1897-vfl-season] The following table can be sorted from biggest winning margin to biggest losing margin for each round.
[src:afl-women-s/1897-vfl-season] If two or more matches in a round are decided by the same margin, these margins are sorted by percentage (i.e. the lowest-scoring winning team is ranked highest and the lowest-scoring losing team is ranked lowest).
[src:afl-women-s/1897-vfl-season] Opponents are listed above the margins and home matches are in bold.
[src:afl-women-s/1898-vfl-grand-final] The **1898 VFL Grand Final** was an Australian rules football game contested between the Essendon Football Club and Fitzroy Football Club, held in Melbourne on 24 September 1898.
[src:afl-women-s/1898-vfl-grand-final] The match was played to determine the premiers for the 1898 VFL season.
[src:afl-women-s/1898-vfl-grand-final] The game was played under atrocious ground conditions in front of 16,538 people at the Junction Oval.
[src:afl-women-s/1898-vfl-grand-final] The match is recognised as the first VFL grand final, although the term "grand final" was not in wide use until 1931.
[src:afl-women-s/1898-vfl-grand-final] It was the first time that Victorian Football League premiership was decided in a final match, as the 1897 premiership was won under a different finals system by Essendon when they finished above three other clubs on the finals series ladder.
[src:afl-women-s/1898-vfl-grand-final] Both Fitzroy back pocket Stan Reid and the Essendon full-forward Charlie Moore later died in South Africa in active service during the Anglo-Boer War—Moore on 5 May 1901, and Reid on 23 June 1901.
[src:afl-women-s/1898-vfl-grand-final] During the 1898 home-and-away season, all teams played each other twice.
[src:afl-women-s/1898-vfl-grand-final] The winners of the two sections were Fitzroy and Collingwood, respectively (for results of all of the round-robin matches); and, a week later (17 September 1898), the two teams played each other at Brunswick Street Oval, with Fitzroy winning the match 2.10 (22) to 1.5 (11).
[src:afl-women-s/1898-vfl-grand-final] After the VFL referred the decision to the VFL's Match Arrangement Committee, they, upon the express instructions of that committee, rejected the suggestions of the two teams outright and the match was controversially scheduled to be played at the Junction Oval.
[src:afl-women-s/1898-vfl-grand-final] The Junction Oval was in an appalling condition, as the ground had not been used since the second Saturday of the sectional round-robin match three weeks earlier (3 September); and, since then, it had been thoroughly top-dressed and "cultivated" in anticipation of the coming cricket season.
[src:afl-women-s/1898-vfl-grand-final] Also, the cricket ground's asphalt cycling track that lay between the boundary line and the fence presented a considerable danger to the footballers.
[src:afl-women-s/1898-vfl-grand-final] Despite being the "challenger", Essendon flatly refused to play in the scheduled match, declaring that it would rather forfeit the match and the premiership than play on such a dangerous surface.
[src:afl-women-s/1898-vfl-grand-final] This view was also strongly supported by Fitzroy, whose captain, Alec Sloan, had also taken the step of signing a statutory declaration to the effect that, in his opinion, the ground was entirely unfit to play on.
[src:afl-women-s/1898-vfl-grand-final] The VFL, perhaps somewhat driven by the fact that the attraction of a finals system was one of the major reasons that the eight teams had left the VFA and formed the VFL in the first place, had a special meeting to hear Essendon's appeal.
[src:afl-women-s/1898-vfl-grand-final] While it chose to endorse the committee's decision, it also did everything it could to convince Essendon to play the match.
[src:afl-women-s/1898-vfl-grand-final] Essendon did not actually agree to play the match until the night before the game; ultimately, this "in-doubt-until-the-last-minute match" was still attended by 16,538 paying spectators; it certainly would have been a much larger crowd otherwise.
[src:afl-women-s/1898-vfl-grand-final] The ground had been in such a dreadful condition that, in the week prior to the match, over 40 dray-loads of rubbish, soil and street-sweepings had been taken from the ground.
[src:afl-women-s/1898-vfl-grand-final] All of this last-minute work greatly improved the playing surface at the ground, with sportswriters noting that while the ground was imperfect, it was nevertheless fit for use.
[src:afl-women-s/1898-vfl-grand-final] Dry, windy weather and patches of ground where the topsoil had not bound meant that players often fell on the grassless slippery ground for want of some sort of grip, and play was often impeded by clouds of dust.
[src:afl-women-s/1898-vfl-grand-final] To prevent any repeat of the events leading up to the 1898 challenge final, the VFL agreed that from 1899 they would schedule for a possible challenge final in advance.
[src:afl-women-s/1898-vfl-grand-final] In 1898, all VFL teams had 20 on-the-field players and no "reserves".
[src:afl-women-s/1898-vfl-grand-final] Although there were no reserves, any player who had left the playing field for any reason at all could resume his place on the field at any time.
[src:afl-women-s/1898-vfl-grand-final] Fitzroy selected a set of brothers in its team: Jim and Mick Grace (see TALK page).
[src:afl-women-s/1898-vfl-grand-final] Essendon had beaten Fitzroy in their round 1 and round 8 matches by 53 and 43 points, respectively.
[src:afl-women-s/1898-vfl-grand-final] Fitzroy had beaten Essendon by 29 points in the third match of their round-robin Sectional matches.
[src:afl-women-s/1898-vfl-grand-final] Both teams had great difficulty playing football in the appalling ground conditions—as evidenced by the low scores—and the tough, bustling Fitzroy team handled the conditions far better than the Essendon team that had hoped to spread the game out as far as possible.
[src:afl-women-s/1898-vfl-grand-final] Fitzroy took the lead in the first few minutes of the match, and Essendon were never able to catch up.
[src:afl-women-s/1898-vfl-grand-final] Essendon were further demoralized when Fitzroy champion forward and follower Mick Grace, renowned for his marking skill and kicking prowess, flew high over a pack to take a spectacular high mark and kicked a long-range goal.
[src:afl-women-s/1898-vfl-grand-final] In a very tight, defensive second half, as the playing conditions deteriorated even further, only one goal was scored.
[src:afl-women-s/1898-vfl-grand-final] Fitzroy went on to beat Essendon 5.8 (38) to 3.5 (23).
[src:afl-women-s/1898-vfl-season] The **1898 VFL season** was the second season of the Victorian Football League (VFL), the highest-level senior Australian rules football competition in Victoria.
[src:afl-women-s/1898-vfl-season] The season featured eight clubs and ran from 14 May to 24 September, comprising a 14-round home-and-away season followed by a finals series featuring all eight clubs.
[src:afl-women-s/1898-vfl-season] Fitzroy won the premiership, defeating Essendon by 15 points in the 1898 VFL grand final; it was Fitzroy's first VFL premiership.
[src:afl-women-s/1898-vfl-season] Essendon won the minor premiership by finishing atop the home-and-away ladder with an 11–3 win–loss record.
[src:afl-women-s/1898-vfl-season] Collingwood's Archie Smith won the leading goalkicker medal as the league's leading goalkicker.
[src:afl-women-s/1898-vfl-season] In 1898, the VFL competition consisted of eight teams of 20 on-the-field players each, with no "reserves" (although any of the 20 players who had left the playing field for any reason could later resume their place on the field at any time during the match).
[src:afl-women-s/1898-vfl-season] Once the 14 round home-and-away season had finished, the 1898 VFL *Premiers* were determined by the specific format and conventions of the 1898 VFL finals system.
[src:afl-women-s/1898-vfl-season] The VFL introduced a new system of finals for the 1898 season.
[src:afl-women-s/1898-vfl-season] The new system, which was used from 1898–1900, allowed all clubs to compete for the major premiership, with the minor premiers having the right to challenge for the premiership.
[src:afl-women-s/1898-vfl-season] By winning the minor premiership and accruing at least eight premiership points from its three sectional matches, Essendon won the right to challenge the semi-final winner for the premiership.
[src:afl-women-s/1899-vfl-grand-final] It was the second annual grand final of the Victorian Football League.
[src:afl-women-s/1899-vfl-grand-final] The match, attended by 4,823 spectators, was won by Fitzroy by a margin of 1 point, becoming the first club to claim back-to-back VFL premierships.
[src:afl-women-s/1899-vfl-grand-final] Fitzroy had won the minor premiership in the 1899 season, while South Melbourne had finished sixth after the home-and-away season.
[src:afl-women-s/1899-vfl-grand-final] In the sectional major rounds, Fitzroy and South Melbourne each finished with records of 3–0 to qualify for the final.
[src:afl-women-s/1899-vfl-grand-final] Under the finals system in place, this match was the final of the major round, played between the two section winners.
[src:afl-women-s/1899-vfl-grand-final] Had South Melbourne won the match, it would not have immediately won the season's premiership; Fitzroy, as the minor premiers, would have had the right to challenge South to a rematch for the premiership on the following Saturday.
[src:afl-women-s/1899-vfl-grand-final] Meanwhile, Fitzroy could clinch the premiership win a win in this match.
[src:afl-women-s/1899-vfl-grand-final] "The last match of the season for the league premiership was played on Saturday, when Fitzroy and South Melbourne met on the St.
[src:afl-women-s/1899-vfl-grand-final] Unfortunately, steady rain, which had fallen all the morning, continued nearly all the afternoon, making the conditions under which the game was played unsatisfactory for the players and most unpleasant for spectators.
[src:afl-women-s/1899-vfl-grand-final] The "weather committee" had not met to consider the advisability of a postponement, and when the teams assembled South Melbourne suggested deferring the match until next Saturday, but Fitzroy preferred to brave the elements.
[src:afl-women-s/1899-vfl-grand-final] The assembling of about 4000 spectators in the unfavorable circumstances indicated clearly that, if the weather had kept fine, the attendance would have been enormous.
[src:afl-women-s/1899-vfl-grand-final] As it was, those present evinced keen interest in the game, every notable bit of good play being heartily cheered.
[src:afl-women-s/1899-vfl-grand-final] Amongst the onlookers were a number of enthusiasts from Geelong, who came up by special train.
[src:afl-women-s/1899-vfl-grand-final] had the ground in splendid order until the rain came, and even after the steady downpour, extending over many hours, it played very, much better than could have been expected, reflecting great credit on the experienced and skilful curator. ...
[src:afl-women-s/1899-vfl-grand-final] The strong wind from the southern end of the ground favoured South Melbourne in the opening quarter.
[src:afl-women-s/1899-vfl-grand-final] Harry Lampe kicked the first two goals of the match, and Fitzroy's only score, a behind, came when a kick from Mick Grace hit the post.
[src:afl-women-s/1899-vfl-grand-final] Fitzroy then had the advantage of the wind in the second quarter.
[src:afl-women-s/1899-vfl-grand-final] Goals to Mick Grace and Fred Fontaine had them ahead at half time.
[src:afl-women-s/1899-vfl-grand-final] Charlie Colgan gave South Melbourne the lead with the only goal of the third term.
[src:afl-women-s/1899-vfl-grand-final] Bill McSpeerin's goal 15 minutes into the final quarter gave Fitzroy the win.
[src:afl-women-s/1899-vfl-grand-final] Fitzroy's Bert Sharpe, the team's centre half-forward in its 1898 premiership side, was a late withdrawal from the side due to the death of his father the day before the Grand Final; his teammates wore black armbands for that match.
[src:afl-women-s/1899-vfl-season] The **1899 VFL season** was the third season of the Victorian Football League (VFL), the highest-level senior Australian rules football competition in Victoria.
[src:afl-women-s/1899-vfl-season] The season featured eight clubs and ran from 13 May to 16 September, comprising a 14-round home-and-away season followed by a finals series featuring all eight clubs.
[src:afl-women-s/1899-vfl-season] Fitzroy won the premiership, defeating South Melbourne by one point in the 1899 VFL grand final; it was Fitzroy's second (consecutive and overall) VFL premiership.
[src:afl-women-s/1899-vfl-season] Fitzroy also won the minor premiership by finishing atop the home-and-away ladder with an 11–3 win–loss record.
[src:afl-women-s/1899-vfl-season] Geelong's Eddy James won his second leading goalkicker medal as the league's leading goalkicker.
[src:afl-women-s/1899-vfl-season] In 1899, the VFL competition consisted of eight teams of 18 on-the-field players each, with no "reserves" (although any of the 18 players who had left the playing field for any reason could later resume their place on the field at any time during the match).
[src:afl-women-s/1899-vfl-season] Once the 14 round home-and-away season had finished, the 1899 VFL *Premiers* were determined by the specific format and conventions of the 1898 VFL finals system.
[src:afl-women-s/1900-vfl-grand-final] The **1900 VFL Grand Final** was an Australian rules football game contested between the Melbourne Football Club and Fitzroy Football Club, held at the East Melbourne Cricket Ground in Melbourne on 22 September 1900.
[src:afl-women-s/1900-vfl-grand-final] It was the 3rd annual Grand Final of the Victorian Football League, staged to determine the premiers for the 1900 VFL season.
[src:afl-women-s/1900-vfl-grand-final] The match, attended by 20,181 spectators, was won by Melbourne by a margin of 4 points.
[src:afl-women-s/1900-vfl-grand-final] The winner of this match would win the premiership.
[src:afl-women-s/1900-vfl-grand-final] Arthur Sowden, and Bill Bowe were unable to play for the Melbourne team, due to injury, and Eric Gardner was unavailable.
[src:afl-women-s/1900-vfl-season] The **1900 VFL season** was the fourth season of the Victorian Football League (VFL), the highest-level senior Australian rules football competition in Victoria.
[src:afl-women-s/1900-vfl-season] The season featured eight clubs and ran from 5 May to 22 September, comprising a 14-round home-and-away season followed by a finals series featuring all eight clubs.
[src:afl-women-s/1900-vfl-season] Melbourne won the premiership, defeating Fitzroy by four points in the 1900 VFL grand final; it was Melbourne's first VFL premiership.
[src:afl-women-s/1900-vfl-season] Fitzroy won its second consecutive minor premiership by finishing atop the home-and-away ladder with an 11–3 win–loss record.
[src:afl-women-s/1900-vfl-season] Geelong's Teddy Lockwood and Essendon's Albert Thurgood tied for the leading goalkicker medal as the league's leading goalkickers.
[src:afl-women-s/1900-vfl-season] In 1900, the VFL competition consisted of eight teams of 18 on-the-field players each, with no "reserves", although any of the 18 players who had left the playing field for any reason could later resume their place on the field at any time during the match.
[src:afl-women-s/1900-vfl-season] Once the 14 round home-and-away season had finished, the 1900 VFL *Premiers* were determined by the specific format and conventions of the 1898 VFL finals system.
[src:afl-women-s/1900-vfl-season] The rescheduling of round 3 until after round 14, which occurred following the cancellation of the originally scheduled matches due to heavy rain, is also reflected in this table.
[src:afl-women-s/1900-vfl-season] By winning the minor premiership and accruing at least eight premiership points from its three sectional matches, Fitzroy won the right to challenge the semi-final winner for the premiership.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] The AFLW is the second most attended women's football competition in Australia (behind A-League Women) and one of the most popular women's football competitions in the world.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] Its average attendance in 2019 of 6,262 per game made it the second-highest of any domestic women's football competition.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] Its record attendance of 53,034 for the 2019 AFL Women's Grand Final was until 2020 the highest match attendance for women's sport in Australia.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] Since launch, the AFLW has attracted an audience of more than 1 million attendees and 2 million viewers and has managed to maintain high interest while moving to primarily ticketed and subscription broadcasting models since the 2021 season.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] It consistently ranks in the top three (alongside cricket and netball) most-watched women's sporting competitions in Australia.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] The league receives international interest, particularly in Ireland, where it has begun to attract a significant television audience due to the ongoing recruitment of Irish Gaelic football stars.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] However, it was reported in mid-2023 that data revealed a significant drop in attendances for the seventh season of the women's league compared to the first season.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] While men playing Australian rules football is documented back to 1858, women's games have only been documented back to 1917, and the first lasting women's league was formed in 1981.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] Women's participation in the sport and the prevalence of women's leagues continued to grow into the 21st century.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] In 2010, the AFL commissioned a report into the state of women's football around the country.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] Following the report, the AFL Commission began working toward the establishment of a national women's league, choosing to establish women's teams in AFL clubs rather than form separate clubs.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] The first on-field step towards the competition took place in early 2013, when the AFL announced an exhibition match to be played between women's teams representing Melbourne and Western Bulldogs in June of that year.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] On 15 May 2013, the first women's draft was held, establishing the playing lists for the two clubs in the forthcoming exhibition match.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] The match played on 29 June 2013 marked the first time two women's sides had competed under the banners of AFL clubs.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] A crowd of 7,518 watched the historic match, which Melbourne won by 35 points.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] The exhibition match became a series between the clubs, with another game played in 2014 and two played in 2015, the last of which – on 16 August 2015 – was the first women's AFL game to be broadcast on free-to-air television.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] It attracted an average audience of 175,000, surpassing the 114,000 average audience for the AFL men's clash of the previous day, between Adelaide and Essendon.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] The success of these exhibition matches prompted the AFL to accelerate its plans for a nationwide women's competition, announcing a preferred start date of 2017.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] Prior to this, the league had announced only aspirational plans to have the women's competition established by 2020.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] The already-planned 2016 exhibition series was expanded at this time, with a total of ten matches to be played in venues across the country and featuring a range of new temporary representative teams.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] In 2016, the AFL opened a process for existing clubs to tender applications to join the new competition.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] The 18 clubs in the men's league had until 29 April 2016 to place a bid for a licence, with 13 clubs making bids: Adelaide, Brisbane, Carlton, Collingwood, Fremantle, Geelong, Greater Western Sydney, Melbourne, North Melbourne, Richmond, St Kilda, West Coast, and Western Bulldogs.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] The AFL's preferred distribution of clubs was four clubs from Victoria and one each from New South Wales, Queensland, South Australia, and Western Australia.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] The inaugural teams were announced on 8 June 2016.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] Adelaide, Brisbane, and Greater Western Sydney were the only teams to bid in their respective states and were granted licences to compete in 2017.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] Both Western Australian clubs made bids, with Fremantle's bid chosen ahead of the bid from West Coast.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] Eight Victorian clubs made bids: Melbourne, Western Bulldogs, Carlton and Collingwood were successful, with Geelong, North Melbourne, Richmond and St Kilda being unsuccessful but granted provisional licences.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] Details about the branding of the league were released in the second half of 2016.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] On 15 September 2016, the AFL announced that the league would be named "AFL Women's" or AFLW for short, with the logo being unveiled on 19 September 2016.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] The logo is a stylised rendition of an Australian rules football ground goal square and goal posts, drawn from a perspective that resembles a "W".
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] On 10 October 2016, the National Australia Bank was named as the league's naming rights sponsor.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] The first premiership game was played at Ikon Park on Friday, 3 February 2017.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] The AFL had initially planned to host the game at Melbourne's Olympic Park Oval, with a capacity of just 7,000, but was forced to change to Ikon Park due to overwhelming interest and a need for more seating.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] The match was deemed a "lockout" with a capacity crowd of 24,568 in attendance, with estimates of a few thousand left outside.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] Gillon McLachlan, the AFL's CEO, personally apologised to those who missed out.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] The game was also a great success on TV, attracting a national audience of 896,000, including 593,000 metropolitan free-to-air viewers, 180,000 regional free-to-air viewers, and 123,000 on Fox Footy.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] The Melbourne metropolitan audience of 424,000 was on par with that of Friday-night AFL men's matches.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] The inaugural season concluded with the Grand Final held on Saturday, 25 March 2017.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] The Adelaide Crows were crowned the league's first premiers after defeating the minor premiers, the Brisbane Lions.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] The scoreline read Adelaide 4.11 (35) def.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] The remaining AFL clubs would join the league in the follow years, with two clubs added in the 2019 season, four in 2020, and the last four in 2022.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] The 10 AFL clubs not originally participating in the competition were invited to bid for inclusion, with priority given to the five clubs that had submitted unsuccessful bids to participate in the inaugural season.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] The deadline to lodge submissions was 16 June 2017.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] The only clubs not to bid were Port Adelaide and Sydney.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] North Melbourne worked with AFL Tasmania to craft its bid, with the club aiming to play home matches in Melbourne, Hobart, and Launceston, and also to select half of its playing list from Tasmania.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] A final decision on which clubs would be admitted to the competition was expected by the end of July 2017, but was delayed several times.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] On 27 September 2017, the AFL announced that Geelong and North Melbourne had been selected to enter the competition in 2019.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] North Melbourne retained its commitment to playing matches in Tasmania.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] The league then added four teams in 2020, with the AFL selecting Gold Coast, Richmond, St Kilda and West Coast to join the competition.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] The growth in clubs for the 2019 season was accompanied by the introduction of an American-style conference structure, which was abandoned after the 2020 season in favour of the traditional single ladder.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, the 2020 season was curtailed and eventually cancelled without a premiership awarded.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] On 12 August 2021, the final four AFL clubs (Essendon, Hawthorn, Port Adelaide and Sydney) were granted licenses, and the league's seventh season in 2022 was the first to feature all 18 AFL clubs.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] North Melbourne became the first expansion team, founded after the inaugural season, to win a premiership, when the Kangaroos defeated Brisbane by 30 points in the 2024 decider, following this up with a 40 point victory in the 2025 Grand Final rematch.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] The competition's 18 teams are based across five states of Australia.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] Ten are based in Victoria (nine in the Melbourne metropolitan area), and New South Wales, Queensland, South Australia and Western Australia have two teams each, while a team from Tasmania will enter the AFLW at a date to be confirmed.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] The Australian Capital Territory and the Northern Territory are the only states or territories not to have AFLW teams.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] Below are the venues that hosted during the 2025 season.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] The club's playing lists were constructed from scratch through the later stages of 2016.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] All participants in the 2017 season were required to be over the age of 17.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] Initially, clubs were asked to nominate a list of desired players, with the AFL assigning two of these "marquee" players to each club.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] In addition, clubs were able to sign a number of players with existing connections to the club, or with arrangements for club-sponsored work or study.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] This number varied for each club, in an attempt to equitably spread talent across the teams.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] In addition, clubs were required to recruit two "rookies" – people with no Australian rules football experience in the previous three-year period.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] The majority of players were later recruited through the 2016 AFL Women's draft.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] The remaining list spots were filled with free-agent signings in the week following the draft.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] In total, clubs have 27 active listed players in addition to injury replacements signed to take the spot of long-term injury-affected players.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] Player salaries are determined by collective bargaining agreement with each club's total payments being determined by a salary cap.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] A significant gender pay gap exists between AFL and the AFLW, with the average wage in the women's league being only 16% of that in the men's league as of 2023.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] Prior to the commencement of the home-and-away season teams are paired off to play an exhibition trial match.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] In 2017, these matches took place during varying weeks of January.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] For the first two seasons of competition, the home-and-away season was operated on a single table, and seven matches were played by each of the eight teams.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] The two highest-placed teams at the conclusion of the home-and-away season qualified for the Grand Final match, in the absence of a longer finals series.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] With the addition of two extra teams in 2019, the AFL Women's home-and-away season introduced conferences, a concept not common in Australian sports.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] The top-two teams from the respective conferences qualified to the preliminary finals, with the first-ranked team in Conference A meeting the second-ranked team in Conference B and the opposite employed for the other preliminary final.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] The winners of those matches then met in the Grand Final.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] The use of conferences was retained in 2020, along with the inclusion of four additional teams.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] The 14 teams were split into two conferences of seven, with teams playing each other team in their conference once.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] The top-four teams in each conference qualified for the finals series.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] The first round of the finals consisted of four knockout finals, with teams from opposite conferences playing against each other, first in Conference A versus fourth in Conference B, and so on.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] This left a final four of North Melbourne, Fremantle, Carlton, and Melbourne, with two rounds of finals to be played.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] At this point, the season was abandoned due to the COVID-19 pandemic, with no 2020 premier.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] In 2021, the league reverted to a single 14-team ladder.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] Each team played 9 matches, with the top six qualifying for a three-week finals series.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] All finals are knockouts, with the top-two teams having a bye in the first round of the finals.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] Since 2022 (S7) the competition has been contested by 18 teams, and the finals series has expanded to eight teams and is played under the AFL final eight system that has been in use in the men's competition since the 2000 season.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] On 21 August 2023, incoming AFL chief executive Andrew Dillon announced that the AFLW will receive equal prize money to the AFL.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] The prize money for AFLW players will almost double, going from $623,922 to $1.1 million to split between the top 8 teams.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] In 2018, the Western Bulldogs and Carlton women's teams held the first Pride game, to celebrate gender diversity, promote inclusion for LGBTIQA+ players, and to help stamp out homophobia.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] St Kilda and Melbourne held a Pride Match in 2020, and the first full AFLW Pride Round was held in 2021.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] An Indigenous Round was established in 2021.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] This round acknowledges the significant contribution of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander women and girls to Australian football and the broader community.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] Each team wears a guernsey especially designed to celebrate Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander culture, and the Dreamtime match is played between Richmond and Essendon.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] An AFLW Indigenous Round Honouree is announced for each season.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] The league peaked at an average attendance of 6,828 in its inaugural season and a record 53,034 attended the 2019 Grand Final.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] Admission was free prior to 2022, when the AFLW introduced reserved ticketing at $10 admission per match, which was later increased.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] In mid-2023, data revealed a significant drop in average attendances for the seventh season compared to the first season.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] Taking into account the greater number of games played, total attendance was still growing, just spread over three times as many matches.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] The league's choice of venues has been criticised, with many of the AFL's premium venues, such as Victoria's Melbourne Cricket Ground and Docklands Stadium, not used for blockbuster AFLW matches.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] The league has been cited as preferring the atmosphere of fuller smaller venues rather than emptier larger venues, particularly for its television broadcasting.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] In its inaugural 2017 season, all matches were televised live by affiliate partners the Seven Network and Fox Footy.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] As part of the initial broadcast deal, the free-to-air carrier Seven broadcast one Saturday-night game per week as standard, in addition to the league's opening match and Grand Final.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] Pay TV network Fox Footy televised all premiership season matches, including simulcasts of the Seven-hosted matches other than the Grand Final.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] The two television networks covered the costs of broadcasting these matches, with no licensing fee payable to the league in exchange.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] *Fearless: The Inside Story of the AFLW* debuted on Disney+ in 2022, the docu-series followed several AFLW clubs through the course of the 2022 season.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] In July 2023 *The Age* reported that AFLW viewer numbers were down 70% from the debut season, blaming a combination of scheduling, poor quality venues and broadcast quality, and "football fatigue".
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] The AFLW has attracted an audience of more than 1 million attendees and 2 million viewers and has managed to maintain high interest despite moving to primarily ticketed and subscription broadcasting models from the 2021 season.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] It consistently ranks in the top three (alongside cricket and netball) most watched women's sporting competitions in Australia.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] The league receives international interest, particularly in Ireland where it has begun to attract a significant television audience due to the ongoing recruitment of Gaelic football stars.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] The official internet/mobile broadcast partner of the AFL is BigPond, part of Telstra.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] The company hosts the league website and those of each of the eight participation clubs.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] The AFL has retained digital broadcast rights to matches in the league's inaugural season and will stream all matches live and free on the league website and mobile app.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] Since 2021, Kayo Sports has streamed all AFLW matches live and on demand in Australia.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] Outside Australia, the inaugural season is available on Watch AFL.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] The National Australia Bank is the league's inaugural and (as of 2022) current naming-rights partner.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] All playing and training equipment, as well as all licensed apparel and hats for the league's clubs, are manufactured by Cotton On.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] Other 2017 league sponsors included Wolf Blass, Chemist Warehouse, and Kellogg's.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] Official match-day attire, together with other club merchandise, is sold through the AFL's stores and website, as well through the clubs and some retailers.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] Prior to the creation of the league, the AFL ran four years of exhibition matches between sides representing Melbourne and Western Bulldogs.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] In 2016, the series was expanded to multiple teams from around the country.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] The best and fairest award determined in the same way as the Brownlow Medal for men, with umpires awarding three, two, and one votes to the best three players in each game, and suspended players are ineligible.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] The MVP award is voted on by the players' peers, in a similar method to the Leigh Matthews Trophy for men.
[src:afl-women-s/afl-women-s] Each week, the senior coach of each club gives five votes to the player they consider to be best on ground in the game in which their team plays, four to the second-best, and so on to one for the fifth-best.
